passages.text: F4Q25 Recap: Struggling to Stay on Track

F4Q beat on rev (+2%) and profitability (+250 bps on op mgn) driven by TPV strength and AP/AR monetization as well as ongoing profitability initiatives.FY26/F1Q topline guidance missed by ~2% and ~1%, respectively, which was attributed to macro-driven conservatism. We think the absolute growth is disappointing and believe the outlook does not leave a path for >20% core growth. We believe shares will remain range-bound NT until mgmt can deliver re-acceleration.

**Solid F4Q Results.** Total and core rev beat consensus by ~2%. Txn rev drove the beat as AP/AR customers increased spend on a SSS basis by 4% y/y and S&E TPV benefited from a continued focus on higher-spending customers. AP/AR monetization benefited from improved ad valorem monetization and the ACH/check pricing increase (AP/AR take rate: +0.003% q/q). Op mgn came in sharply ahead of expectations driven by ongoing profitability improvements. **See Exhibit 1 for full** **F4Q results vs. expectations and incremental commentary.**

**What is** **Baked** **into** **the** **Guidance?** FY26 total and core rev guidance for $1,589.5-1,629.5m (+9-11% y/y) and $1,450.5-1,490.5m (+12-15% y/y), respectively, both missed consensus by ~2%. For F1Q,total and core rev guidance of $385-395m (+7-10% y/y) and $348-358m (+11-14% y/y) each fell short of the Street by ~1%. On profitability, FY26 and F1Q guidance for adj. op income of $240-270m (15-17% mgn) and $53.5-58.5m (14-15% mgn), respectively, fell short of consensus by ~5% and ~13% each. BILL called out prudence in the guidance driven by macro uncertainty and is assuming flat TPV/customer across the portfolio. Furthermore, mgmt expects similar AP/AR take rate expansion in FY26 vs. FY25. S&E monetization is expected to come in at the lower end of the 250-260 bp range driven by a mix shift towards lower-take rate spend categories. Encouragingly,BILL will fully lap policy changes within the advertising segment and the related S&E headwind by F2Q26. Mgmt expects growth to accelerate in FY2H driven by multiple scaling initiatives across the platform.

**Taking** **Steps** **to** **Moderate** **SBC.** SBC is expected to be $290m for FY26, representing 18% of total rev. Mgmt called out an enhanced focus on GAAP profitability and expectations to significantly reduce grant value, tighten eligibility criteria, and shorten vesting periods for FY26. However, mgmt does not expect the full impact to benefit SBC as a % of rev until expenses related to prior grants wind down.

Our \(\) 70\$ price target is derived from a discounted cash flow analysis that models unlevered free cash flows through 2030. Risks to our price target include slower adoption of digital B2B payment solutions, competitive threats from industry participants, loss of a large channel partner, short- duration contracts, and lower interest rates.
